		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Separation of concerns</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>In <a href="/wiki/Computer_science" title="Computer science">computer science</a>, <b>separation of concerns</b> (<b>SoC</b>) is the process of breaking a <a href="/wiki/Computer_program" title="Computer program">computer program</a> into distinct features that overlap in functionality as little as possible. A <a href="/wiki/Concern_(computer_science)" title="Concern (computer science)">concern</a> is any piece of interest or focus in a program. Typically, concerns are synonymous with <a href="/wiki/Feature" title="Feature">features</a> or behaviors. Progress towards SoC is traditionally achieved through <a href="/wiki/Modularity_(programming)" title="Modularity (programming)" class="mw-redirect">modularity</a> and <a href="/wiki/Encapsulation_(computer_science)" title="Encapsulation (computer science)">encapsulation</a>, with the help of <a href="/wiki/Information_hiding" title="Information hiding">information hiding</a>. Layered designs in information systems are also often based on separation of concerns (e.g., presentation layer, business logic layer, data access layer, database layer).</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
<td>
<div id="toctitle">
